english:
  title: A Banquet Held by Duke Yang Anbo for the Grand Commander and Prince Shen at the Jade Spring Hall
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The splendid lakeside mansion stands as the rumors told—
    the Duke opens wide his feast to gladden our sovereign lord.
    A thousand cups of finest wine flow from the cormorant ladle,
    beauties of eighteen summers dance in jade-green silk.

    Through the fragrance of lotus blooms drifts the sound of passing rain,
    and clouds drift past the shadows of the reeds.
    Before the music and song have ceased their revels,
    the chariot wheels already clatter with the fading day—
    the western hills grow dim as dusk descends.
  footnotes:
    - The 'cormorant ladle' (鸕鷀杓) refers to a ladle shaped like a cormorant's head, used in serving wine at noble gatherings.
    - The 'beauties of eighteen summers' is a classical Chinese poetic expression for lovely young women at the height of their beauty.
    - The 'jade spring hall' (玉淵堂) was likely a famous pavilion known for its beauty and as a venue for aristocratic entertainments.
